      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Observed order of accuracy must be within 10% of theoretical order for the discretization scheme employed.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions was applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations. Observed spatial order of accuracy of 1.97 was confirmed against the expected second-order scheme, meeting the 10% tolerance criterion. Results are documented in the solver verification report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI on the fine mesh must be below 5% for the primary quantity of interest (relative hemolysis index).",
      "rationale": "A three-level grid convergence study was performed. GCI on the fine mesh (12.8M cells) was 1.3% for the relative hemolysis index at the 2.5 L/min operating point, well within the 5% acceptance threshold. Asymptotic range of convergence was confirmed (GCI ratio = 1.02). Detailed results are discussed in the validation narrative but the formal evidence record for this activity remains pending final archival."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match CFD boundary conditions within stated uncertainty bounds for flow rate (±5%) and rotational speed (±2%).",
      "rationale": "In-vitro experiments were conducted at the same 5 flow-speed combinations used in CFD. Flow rate was controlled to ±2.1% and rotational speed to ±0.8%, both within acceptance bounds. Temperature was maintained at 37°C ± 0.5°C to match blood viscosity assumptions in the model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mean absolute error in relative hemolysis index between CFD and experiment must be less than 15% across all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Comparison of CFD-predicted and experimentally measured relative hemolysis index across all 5 operating points yielded a mean absolute error of 9.2%. Maximum point-wise error was 12.4% at the 6 L/min, 2800 RPM condition. All errors are within the 15% acceptance criterion, supporting model credibility for the intended COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) must be directly linked to the clinical decision criterion and computed from model outputs without surrogate substitution.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index is computed directly from CFD-predicted shear stress and exposure time fields using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model. This QoI maps directly to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate device) and is the same metric used in the experimental comparison, confirming relevance without surrogate substitution."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry and fluid (or well-characterized blood analog) as the COU, with operating conditions spanning the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry with porcine blood at physiological hematocrit (40%). Operating conditions covered the full 5-point COU envelope (2.5–6 L/min, 2800–3500 RPM). The validation scenario is therefore directly representative of the COU without geometric or fluid surrogates."
    },
